<span id="freeTextContainer5520292194107565908">I wanted to give this book a 3-star rating. I did at first, but my conscience cannot allow it anymore. So the actual rating falls on 2.5 stars.<br/><br/>I really wanted to love this book. I started it with high expectations and it was good. I did like the writhing style, the story, and the perspective of an Armenian woman in Iran. The story was fast and very easy to read. But there was a big problem. For me at least.<br/><br/>I thought this book was about a woman who realizes she has never really lived for herself.</span>
  <span id="freeText5520292194107565908" style="display:none">I wanted to give this book a 3-star rating. I did at first, but my conscience cannot allow it anymore. So the actual rating falls on 2.5 stars.<br /><br />I really wanted to love this book. I started it with high expectations and it was good. I did like the writhing style, the story, and the perspective of an Armenian woman in Iran. The story was fast and very easy to read. But there was a big problem. For me at least.<br /><br />I thought this book was about a woman who realizes she has never really lived for herself. She has always done what is expected of her and kept her head out of trouble. She does her duties as a wife and a mother. And it IS about that. Clarice realizes that she is not really satisfied with her life. Here's where the problem starts. She never says anything. She avoids conversations altogether, avoids conflicts, and avoids voicing her thoughts (because her father advised her to do that,) and then she blames others for never knowing that she also needs something (she also does that in her head, not aloud). Now, that's also fine in the starting point. But Clarice never does anything to change that throughout the story. She doesn't really take any considerable action. She never talks to her husband or her family and remains a passive character until everyone changes suddenly and then everything is good. I expected more. I expected her to do something before the end. She does start doing something new in the end but that is after everyone has already changed their behavior and she hasn't said a word about it. <br /><br />As a woman living in Iran, I am faced with this problem everyday. I see it in older generation women in my life and I don't think women in Iran need anymore encouragement to be more passive. People can't read your mind if you never say anything. I don't think women should be silent in voicing their feelings to this extent. You should say so if something is wrong not be proper and good and never say a word till a miracle happens. <br /><br />Again I was really excited about this book because I thought Clarice is gonna take a stand against the old-fashioned culture around her, but I was disappointed. Still the book had potential and it was enjoyable to some extent but I wished for more. It's a different read among Persian books and I think people can still enjoy it despite all that.</span>
